The McDowell Institute for Teacher Excellence in Positive Behavior Support, housed in the College of Education at Bloomsburg University, is a unique component of the institution’s teacher preparation programs that was established in 2012. The McDowell Institute is designed to equip educators with strategies, practices, and experiences to effectively support the academic, social, and emotional growth of all students. The Institute provides all teacher candidates with the social-emotional training that is needed by today’s teachers, and is required by our state and local agencies. This training includes “Youth Mental Health First Aid Training” as well as modules on social emotional learning topics that are integrated in coursework throughout the curriculum. The modules include topics such as trauma, adverse childhood experiences, rapport as a protective factor, building resiliency, positive reinforcement, bully prevention, and general social-emotional learning.

We work closely with the Pittsburgh Public Schools and participate in the PPS School District University Collaborative.  Carlow University is a member of the Executive and Operations Committees of this collaborative.  There are five institutions of higher education who are full members and who meet quarterly with the school district leaders, including the Deputy Superintendent, to assure that universities are responsive to the employment needs of urban school districts.  The operations committee meets quarterly and consists of individual school liaisons, principals,  university field placement faculty, and student teaching supervisors. This committee oversees student teaching seminars and logistics related to professional development collaborations and placements for student teachers in the district.

Chatham University provides education students the opportunity to complete field placements in a varied assortment of schools.  This includes schools with socio-economic, ethnic, racial, language, geographical and academic diversity. Chatham students experience applied teaching in these diverse settings which helps pre-service teachers prepare for working with students of various backgrounds, abilities and needs. In addition, coursework in all education programs teach about diversity. Specific courses that address various student needs include Issues of Poverty  in Education, Diverse Family and Community Partnerships, Inclusion, EL Strategies for Classroom Teachers, Differentiated Reading and Writing, Teaching in Urban Schools, and Perspectives in Education.

Chestnut Hill College embeds strong content and pedagogical content to major topics such as children with special needs, diversity in learning and language, assessment, and families and communities. These topics help students make connections between theory and practice and are important for students to develop a deep understanding of practice and to articulate why and how decisions are made in the best interest of children. Students are trained to use local and state standards to drive their instruction, decision-making, planning, and assessments. Chestnut Hill College faculty from the Education Department work as mentors to address instructional decisions new teachers face in the classroom. This includes offering help in the form of providing IEP writing supports, classroom management plans, how to prepare for Back-to-School-Nights and parent conferences, as well as providing consultation regarding discipline to those who may be experiencing behavioral challenges in the classroom.

Teacher candidates in the Leading Teacher Program (Undergraduate and Graduate) use PA Academic Standards and Assessment Anchors and the new PA Common Core Standards as well as professional standards in the content areas, and student assessments to inform the design of instruction through lesson planning and revisions in each of the content methods courses and field experiences integrated with the methods courses, as well as student teaching.  Furthermore, in foundations courses, special education courses, and methods courses candidates examine standardized assessments used locally, as well as nationally, and learn to interpret the results of these assessments and their implications for student learning and assessing teacher effectiveness. According to Pennsylvania legislation, all teacher candidates must receive 9 credits of instruction in special education methods and 3 credits of instruction related to limited English proficient students.  All of our teacher certification programs exceed this requirement by requiring 15 credits of special education instructional methods, including 3 credits of instruction related to limited English proficient students.  In addition, the PreK-4 Teacher Education Major is automatically combined with PreK-8 Special Education Certification, so that all teacher candidates who complete the PreK-4 Teacher Education Certification Program have dual certification with PreK-8 Special Education.
Pennsylvania also allows graduates with PreK-8 Special Education Certification to "add-on" 7-12th grade Special Education Certification by completing additional coursework. Candidates are placed in geographically and demographically diverse field placements and experiences beginning freshman year and continuing through student teaching. Our coursework and field experiences explicitly address ways to serve underrepresented and marginalized populations including but are not limited to students and families with disabilities and low socioeconomic status. We also work to prepare teachers to cultivate and draw from the linguistic and cultural resources of students, families, and communities in school. This includes coursework related to serving English learners and students of color.

In order to accomplish these assurances Lancaster Bible College employs specific strategies. Seminars are held each year to inform the students of current trends and legislation affecting schools. The curriculum includes courses (Exceptional Child, Teaching The English Language Learner, and Inclusionary Practices) where the objectives directly address the needs of students with disabilities, limited English proficiency, and those from low-income families. During the semester prior to student teaching, all prospective teachers participate in weekly field placements in urban schools where the student populations are inclusive of these levels of needs.

LBC surveys local LEAs to receive feedback on teacher candidates and program effectiveness.

Our teacher certification-preparation curricula address aspects of cultural, socioeconomic and linguistic diversity appropriate to each course. These programs include heavy emphasis on RTII and inclusion. Special education candidates take general education methods courses, just as general education candidates take multiple special education methods courses.  Required content methods courses focus on adapting curriculum, assessments, and instructional implementation for English Language Learners based on WIDA English Development standards.  At the secondary level, we do our best to place each candidate in either an urban or suburban setting for the 4-week extended stage 3 pre-student-teaching experience and then in the other setting for student teaching.  Because of our geographic location, we do not place candidates in rural settings.

These agreements and resources allow students to have access to training and working with a multitude of different student populations. Mansfield University has developed a core of special education coursework designed for all education programs.  These courses examine the skill levels and needs of persons who are exceptional in emotional, social, physical, and intellectual development.  Discussions include key historical foundations, major legislation, laws and policies, identification procedures, placement options, and current issues and trends in special education.  Focus is on examination of current trends and issues in Second Language Acquisition (SLA), theoretical notions and research in the study of language acquisition, enculturation, acculturation, and cognitive development.

Students in our programs have numerous requirements and opportunity for clinical work and these experiences include purposeful study of the demographics of their placements.  Our placements include both rural and urban settings.

The institution employs several strategies to assure compliance including:  1)  requiring all certification candidates to complete nine credits of special education coursework and three credits of working with English language learners;  2) requiring all candidates to complete field experience in at least one urban, suburban and rural school setting;  3) requiring all teacher candidates to complete a teacher work sample which assesses their ability to plan, modify, assess instruction for all learners in the classroom, and to reflect and make changes during and after lessons.

AssuranceComments: Candidates who enroll in the intern certificate program must take nine credits prior to starting a supervised internship where they are employed as a long-term substitute or full-time teacher of record. Included in these credits are courses in educational psychology or foundations, special education, and general teaching methods.  The content in these courses focuses on teaching students with diverse needs. One requirement of the intern program is that candidates must be continuously enrolled in coursework required for an Instructional I certificate.  All intern candidates are required to complete nine credits of coursework in special education and three credits of working with English Language Learners prior to recommendation for an Instructional I certificate.
CHFNM: Sister Mary Persico, I.H.M., Ed. D.

The EPP surveys school leadership on an annual basis for continuous feedback on school needs and teacher preparation.

Unit Assessment System Protocol to Document Assurances:  
Shippensburg University is committed to collecting data to assess candidates’ performance at the course level and throughout their programs. Faculty members teaching or supervising a data-rich course (i.e., methods, student teaching or practicum) will continue to collect and analyze data according to the Unit Assessment System Protocol. Nine credits of coursework in: Collaboration and Inclusion of students with special education needs (3 credits), Special education instructional strategies (6 credits), and an additional 3 credits in teaching English Language Learners.  

Our university is located in an urban setting and our students get experience visiting, observing, and assisting teachers who are teaching in community schools.  Many of the students in our Intern Program are either working in the School District of Philadelphia, or the low-resource school district of Chester-Upland.  In the past, many of our interns have gone on to be hired in these school districts.

ASSURANCES
Wilkes University Education Department provides training to prospective teachers in keeping with the identified recruitment/hiring needs of regional schools and nearby states. This preparation begins with the earliest Education classes taken in students’ first year and culminates in the clinical semester of student teaching. Throughout students' coursework and field experiences, they have ample opportunities to be in the local schools each semester and identify their specific needs. By interacting with their mentoring and cooperating teachers in these area schools, students see first-hand the challenges and the needs of students from districts with high-needs SES population and low resources.
